With React you can basically build components, compose and even reuse them wherever you can and you wouldn&#39;t even need FreeMarker, however, if you do need to use FreeMarker, you can check the docs [here][1]. For example, let&#39;s say your insurance module has `policy-details` and `insured-asset` (excuse the poor domain concepts). You can essentially have the two components independently and one that brings the two together, say `insurance-module` for example and the code would look like so:

PolicyDetails.js/InsuredAsset.js

```JavaScript
import React, { Component } from &#39;react&#39;
...

export class PolicyDetails extends Component {
   //constructor and maybe other functions
   render() {
     return (
       &lt;div&gt;
          some html here...
       &lt;/div&gt;
      )
   }

}
```

And for the composite component you can have something like:

InsuranceComponent.js
```JavaScript
import React, { Component } from &#39;react&#39;
...

export class InsuranceComponent extends Component {
   //constructor and maybe other functions
   render() {
     return (
       &lt;div&gt;
          &lt;PolicyDetails /&gt;
          &lt;InsuredAsset /&gt;
       &lt;/div&gt;
      )
   }

}
```

I hope this answers your question as it was a bit too broad to give a specific answer


  [1]: http://freemarker.js.org

It is possible to use react components in .ftl files. You have to transpile the code afterwards. &lt;br&gt;This is possible by using **Babel**. &lt;br&gt; Write your react component like so: &lt;br&gt; **PolicyDetails.js**
```
const {useEffect, useState, Component} = React;
const PolicyDetails =()=&gt;{
some js here...
 render() {
     return (
       &lt;div&gt;
          some html here...
       &lt;/div&gt;
      )
   }
}
ReactDOM.render(&lt;Query/&gt;, document.getElementById(&quot;PolicyDetails&quot;));

```
**index.html**
```
...
&lt;script src=&quot;https://unpkg.com/react@17/umd/react.development.js&quot; crossorigin&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src=&quot;https://unpkg.com/react-dom@17/umd/react-dom.development.js&quot; crossorigin&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src=&quot;https://unpkg.com/@babel/standalone/babel.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src=&quot;pathToJsFile/PolicyDetails.js&quot; type=&quot;text/babel&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
...
&lt;div id = &quot;PolicyDetails&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
...

```
You need the imported script for react to work. The problem is that you can&#39;t use react fully with import/export which makes it pretty messy code. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;If you have a solution for this problem I would be thankful because I&#39;m doing the same kind of thing in my company.

