&gt; _&quot;How can I store data in java, so that I can access it by any of the stored fields, without having to store the data multiple times? ...&quot;_

I don&#39;t believe there is any inherent way to do this in Java.

Although, you won&#39;t have to store it multiple times to achieve the effect.

If there is an abstraction, it would most-likely be part of the _[Collections](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/package-summary.html#JavaCollectionsFramework)_ framework.  
Here is the link to the _JavaDoc_, if you&#39;d like to review the available interfaces.  
_[Collections Framework Overview (Java SE 20 &amp;amp; JDK 20)](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/doc-files/coll-overview.html)_.

&gt; _&quot;... is there any way to store that data, so that I not only get the fruit by their name, but for example also get all fruits that are yellow. or all fruits with the count 4? ...&quot;_

I recommend just creating a separate method, for each look-up.

You can utilize the _ArrayList_ to store the data.  
These will return a list of matches, considering there may be more than one result&amp;mdash;or _null_, when no match is found.

```java
List&lt;Fruit&gt; findName(String string, List&lt;Fruit&gt; list) {
    List&lt;Fruit&gt; results = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    for (Fruit fruit : list) {
        if (fruit.name.equals(string)) results.add(fruit);
    }
    return results.size() == 0 ? null : results;
}

List&lt;Fruit&gt; findColor(String string, List&lt;Fruit&gt; list) {
    List&lt;Fruit&gt; results = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    for (Fruit fruit : list) {
        if (fruit.Color.equals(string)) results.add(fruit);
    }
    return results.size() == 0 ? null : results;
}

List&lt;Fruit&gt; findCount(int value, List&lt;Fruit&gt; list) {
    List&lt;Fruit&gt; results = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    for (Fruit fruit : list) {
        if (fruit.count == value) results.add(fruit);
    }
    return results.size() == 0 ? null : results;
}
```

And, here is an example.

```java
Fruit f1 = new Fruit(&quot;banana&quot;,&quot;yellow&quot;,4);
Fruit f2 = new Fruit(&quot;apple&quot;,&quot;red&quot;,2);
Fruit f3 = new Fruit(&quot;tomato&quot;,&quot;red&quot;,4);

List&lt;Fruit&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(List.of(f1, f2, f3));

System.out.println(findName(&quot;apple&quot;, list));
System.out.println(findColor(&quot;red&quot;, list));
System.out.println(findCount(4, list));
```

Output

```none
[apple]
[apple, tomato]
[banana, tomato]
```

You can use `groupByEach` from [Eclipse Collections][1] to group an item by multiple keys. 

    record Fruit(String name, String color, int count) {}
    
    @Test
    public void groupFruitByNameAndColorAndCount()
    {
        Fruit f1 = new Fruit(&quot;banana&quot;, &quot;yellow&quot;, 4);
        Fruit f2 = new Fruit(&quot;apple&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, 2);
        Fruit f3 = new Fruit(&quot;tomato&quot;, &quot;red&quot;, 4);
        MutableList&lt;Fruit&gt; fruit = Lists.mutable.of(f1, f2, f3);
    
        ListMultimap&lt;Object, Fruit&gt; index =
            fruit.groupByEach(each -&gt; List.of(each.name, each.color, each.count));
    
        Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f1), index.get(&quot;banana&quot;));
        Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f2), index.get(&quot;apple&quot;));
        Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f3), index.get(&quot;tomato&quot;));
        Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f1), index.get(&quot;yellow&quot;));
        Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f2, f3), index.get(&quot;red&quot;));
        Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f1, f3), index.get(4));
        Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f2), index.get(2));
    }

Because the keys are different types, `String` (name), `String` (color) and `Integer` (count), the type of the key in the `ListMultimap` has to be `Object`.

I would normally recommend using multiple `groupBy` calls to index data by different types.

    ListMultimap&lt;String, Fruit&gt; fruitByName = fruit.groupBy(Fruit::name);
    ListMultimap&lt;String, Fruit&gt; fruitByColor = fruit.groupBy(Fruit::color);
    ListMultimap&lt;Integer, Fruit&gt; fruitByCount = fruit.groupBy(Fruit::count);

In both cases, there will be references to the same `Fruit` instances stored in multiple Lists. The data itself will not be copied, just the references.

It is possible to iterate over the fruit once and update three Multimap indices using a combination of `asLazy`, `tap` and `forEach`.

    MutableListMultimap&lt;String, Fruit&gt; byName = Multimaps.mutable.list.empty();
    MutableListMultimap&lt;String, Fruit&gt; byColor = Multimaps.mutable.list.empty();
    MutableListMultimap&lt;Integer, Fruit&gt; byCount = Multimaps.mutable.list.empty();
    fruit.asLazy()
            .tap(each -&gt; byName.put(each.name, each))
            .tap(each -&gt; byColor.put(each.color, each))
            .forEach(each -&gt; byCount.put(each.count, each));
    
    Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f1), byName.get(&quot;banana&quot;));
    Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f2, f3), byColor.get(&quot;red&quot;));
    Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f1, f3), byCount.get(4));

If you don&#39;t want to create an index for lookups, and don&#39;t mind the cost of multiple iterations of the fruit `List`, then you could just use Java `Stream` to `filter` the data you want. 

    List&lt;Fruit&gt; bananaList = fruit.stream()
            .filter(each -&gt; &quot;banana&quot;.equals(each.name))
            .toList();
    Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f1), bananaList);
    
    List&lt;Fruit&gt; redList = fruit.stream()
            .filter(each -&gt; &quot;red&quot;.equals(each.color))
            .toList();
    Assertions.assertEquals(List.of(f2, f3), redList);


**Note:** I am a committer for Eclipse Collections

  [1]: https://github.com/eclipse/eclipse-collections

